"Miraculous" Recovery of a Peshawar Massacre Survivor
A paralysed teenager who had been shot four times in the most brutal terrorist attack in Pakistan managed a "miracle" recovery after treatment in the United Kingdom.
Mohamed Ibrahim Khan, 13 years old, the doctors in Pakistan had told him that he would never be able to go.
At least 140 people, most children, were killed when armed men attacked the public school of the Peshawar army last December.
Mohamed, who arrived in London last month for surgery, will be released later from the hospital.
Just nine months ago, on an ordinary Tuesday morning, Mohamed was sitting at his first hour of help and listening carefully to his teachers.
Right then, seven armed men dressed in the uniforms of security agents entered the army's public school.
They wore belts with explosives and had to carry out a simple mission: to kill all the men, women, and children in their way.
“I can’t forget what happened that day,” Mohamed says with a rough look.
I was sitting in the amphitheater, asking questions... then I heard gunfire outside.
The terrorists went inside, and they started killing our professor was burned alive.
Mohamed describes how he pulled four students out of the amphitheater while the carnagi was taking place.
Then he says he heard his friend, Hamza, yelling at him.
He said, "Oh, brother, save me."
I held him by his hand.
Then I was shot in the back, and he in the head.
Most of the people killed in the attack were students
Hamza died in Mohamed's arms.
Mohamed remembers that immediately after that he fainted and that the next thing he knew was that he was on a hospital bed, paralyzed from the waist down.
The doctors in Peshawar in northern Pakistan, then the doctors in Rawalpindi, near the capital, told his family that there was no treatment and that he would never be able to go.
"When I saw him, I felt how my soul came out," says Sher Khan, Mohamed's father.
Those nine months were the hardest in my life.
But Khan and his wife, Sherbano, refused to believe that their son so passionate about cricket would never be able to use his feet again.
They campaigned and asked for help from Pakistani television, attracting support from famous people such as Imran Khan, a cricket player becoming a politician.
Finally, they managed to raise funds to take Mohamed to the United Kingdom and give him treatment at the Harley Street private clinic in London.
The consultant's neurosurgeon Irfan Malik described Mohamed as "fearful" when he arrived at the hospital.
“He had spent his last [some] months lying in bed, without being able to move from one side to the other,” says Malik.
He was weak, he put a lot of pressure on his back.
He wasn't in too good shape.
A vertebrae at the base of Mohamed's spine had been destroyed
Mohamed had been shot in his shoulder, hip and back during the attack, and the lower spine had been destroyed, leading to paralysis.
However, during a six - hour operation, Malik and his team were able to reconnect the nerve endings and rebuild the destroyed part of the column.
Even Malik was surprised at what happened next.
Exactly a week after the operation, Mohamed got up and started taking steps and going.
We didn't expect such a good outcome.
It was a miracle," he says.
In less than two weeks after the operation, Mohamed is ready to leave the hospital and start the long recovery process.
Mohamed challenged fate and began to go again
He wants to become strong and to continue his studies in the United Kingdom.
But he is determined to return to Pakistan, join the army and fight terrorism.
"I feel like I still have a chance to live," he says, showing pictures of guns drawn by him next to school manuals and pens
Physically, Mohamed is getting stronger every day, but psychological trauma that goes through and now is unimaginable.
"My fury has not fallen," he confesses.
In my school, little children were killed.
What crime did they commit?
His mother wipes a tear, cheers him up, and says: “I see my son walking again.”
He'll be able to continue to be living.
