A new study shows that more people die from air pollution than malaria and HIV/AIDS
According to a new reference study, over 3 million people die prematurely each year because of air pollution from outside, more than malaria and HIV/AIDS together.
The main cause, especially in Asia, is wood and coal burned for heating homes and cooking, but research reveals that an equally alarming reason is agricultural emissions from Europe and the United States, which is the main reason for these deaths.
The report warns that if no action is taken, the number of deaths - already equivalent to six deaths per minute - will double by 2050.
"These projections should draw an alarm signal for public health agencies all over the world," said Professor Michael Jerrett, environmental health expert at the University of California, who was not involved in research.
Most of the deaths caused by the rain of the air are caused by tiny particles that can be inhaled deep into the lungs.
They cause stroke and stroke, which are responsible for three quarters of the 3.3 million deaths annually, while the rest are caused by lung cancer and respiratory diseases.
Research has not included the effects of indoor air pollution, e.g. from cooking fires, which are estimated to cause 3.4 million deaths per year.
The new study, published in Nature newspaper, is the first one to highlight various sources of air pollution from outside and estimated the number of premature deaths caused by these, taking into account road traffic, fossil fuel-based plants and other sources.
Researchers have used a detailed computerized model of the global atmosphere to assess the impact of air pollution on different populations, including new information on how pollution affects Chinese and Indian residents.
A third of all premature deaths were the result of the use of smoke-extinguishing fuels, such as wood and coal, for heating homes or cooking, and the use of dirty diesel generators for electricity, all of which are recognized dangers.
The consumption of this type of internal energy causes half of the 645 000 deaths per year in India and a third of the 1.4 million deaths per year in China.
However, the research found that agricultural ammonia emissions had a "remarkable" impact, according to Professor Jos Lelieveld of the German Institute of Chemical Max Planck, which led the research.
A fifth of global deaths are caused by these emissions, mainly from cattle, birds and pigs and from the over-use of fertilizers.
Amoniac reacts with traffic and industry exhaust gases and produces tiny particles, being the main reason of death due to air pollution in the east of the United States, Japan and Europe.
"For London, agriculture is the main source," says Lelieveld.
Throughout the United Kingdom, 48% of premature deaths were the result of agricultural pollution.
Traffic pollution is still an important factor in developed countries, causing a fifth of deaths, despite measures against polluting vehicles.
This has caused only 5% of deaths globally, but the figure could increase as more and more cars appear on the streets in developing countries.
Air pollution by the power plant, in particular by those operating with coal, was significant globally, causing one of the seven deaths.
In the US it is the main single factor, causing a third of the 55,000 deaths per year, compared with 16% in the United Kingdom.
Natural air pollution, especially in the arid regions and with much dust, has caused almost a fifth of the deaths globally caused by air pollution.
This source is a major factor in some arid countries, being responsible for 92% of the deaths in Egypt and 81% in Iran.
“The overlap between the high degree of pollution and the high number of residents says the word about public health, but there’s nothing more known about pollution sources responsible for premature deaths,” says Jerrett.
The results are surprising and potentially important for the protection of public health at the global level.
It is now assumed that all particles are as toxic as they are.
But if fuel burning is more toxic, as some scientists suspect, the percentage of premature deaths that can be attributed to agricultural emissions would be lower.
Even so, Jerrett says "discovery is very valuable... because agriculture has not generally been seen as a major source of air pollution or premature death and suggests that much more attention should be paid to agricultural sources, both from scientists and political leaders."
Dr. Oliver Wild, an atmosphere specialist at Lancaster University in the United Kingdom, said: “The study really highlights the need for air quality control, in order to avoid these deaths, especially in areas very populated in Asia.”
