I don't think it's going to happen that way, but it seems premature to talk about the great and inevitable electoral defeat over five years, of a leader chosen the other day.
Now, however, we can refer to procedures: we have witnessed a democratic exercise of an impressive scope.
The British Labour did not invent the voting system directly for the party leader, in the western left.
French scientists have been practicing for a few years a more complicated system, based on motions, which allows the expression of all members and supporters; in addition, they have organised a preliminary competition for the nomination of the candidate to the presidentials of 2012.
However, the internal election of workers seems more spectacular and more political, as the new leader chosen automatically becomes his peak of launch in future elections.
It is, of course, also a matter of political system, the customization of power being more pronounced in the UK than on the other side of the Channel of Man.
In addition, participation in the vote was great in all three "searches": members themselves, members of the unions and other organisations affiliated to the party and, finally, the group of supporters (who received the ballot after a summary of the registration procedure).
This last group gives us interesting information about the perceptions of the left segments of British society, especially those of young or middle-aged people, educated, interested in the political phenomenon.
Many of them will choose to engage more, in the future, precisely because of the signal offered by Corbyn's victory.
There is, as far as I know, sociological surveys that tell us too much about the attitudes of this laborious "external search", so careful speculation is allowed.
I think we have a lot of attitudes similar to those of the sympathizers Podemos (Spain) or even SYRIZA (Greece), with the observation that they will travel through the traditional channels of the left.
If we have to identify a "anti-system" vocation, it is primarily reflected by rejecting the centrist line, New Labour (for many, only a simulated form of much-thatcherism).
The second component would be the repudiation of the leaders considered guilty by the two successive electoral failures, one of the arguments being that they did not go far enough left, that they were not firmly delimited by the Tony Blair era.
The second - I think, and more suggestive - is offered by the recent referendum on Scotland's independence.
If we take a break from the separatist message and focus strictly on aspirations for other political themes, we see how Scottish nationalists have captured the energies of public segments favorable to the social state and animated by the aspiration of equity, disarmament supporters and hostiles of military involvement across the border, but also sensitive to the new themes of the left: ecology, gender, assistance for poor countries.
Scottish workers have thus lost an electorate to which they should have, at least in principle, privileged access, but which they can now recover (see their enthusiasm towards Corbyn’s campaign).
Like energy exists everywhere in the United Kingdom, but the old leadership couldn't attract them.
Jeremy Corbyn, with his vocation as an outsider, has more chances of success than Ed Miliband, the "aristocrat" laborist.
The comparison with Scotland tells us more, I believe, than the one with the left anti-Sistema from the southern periphery of Europe.
The term "anti-system" is too hard: "anti-establishment" seems more appropriate to me.
Until next week we will learn more about Jeremy Corbyn's first step as the leader of the opposition.
We will see if the red flag will not come back in the House of Commons (it would not be for the first time), after the new leader will have occupied his place, first of all the opposition banks.
